ing import List\nfrom collections import defaultdict\n\nclass Solution:\n    def subarraysWithKDistinct(self, nums: List[int], k: int) -> int:\n        def atMostKDistinct(nums, k):\n            count = defaultdict(int)\n            left = 0\n            result = 0\n            \n            for right in range(len(nums)):\n                count[nums[right]] += 1\n                \n                while len(count) > k:\n                    count[nums[left]] -= 1\n                    if count[nums[left]] == 0:\n                        del count[nums[left]]\n                    left += 1\n                \n                result += right - left + 1\n            \n            return result\n        \n        return atMostKDistinct(nums, k) - atMostKDistinct(nums, k - 1)\n```\n\n### Explanation:\n\n1. **Helper Function `atMostKDistinct`**:\n   - This function calculates the number of subarrays with at most `k` distinct integers.\n   - It uses a sliding window approach with two pointers, `left` and `right`.\n   - A dictionary `count` keeps track of the frequency of elements in the current window.\n   - As we expand the window by moving `right`, we add the current element to the count.\n   - If the number of distinct elements in the window exceeds `k`, we shrink the window from the left until the number of distinct elements is at most `k`.\n   - The number of subarrays ending at `right` and starting from any index between `left` and `right` is `right - left + 1`.\n\n2. **Main Function `subarraysWithKDistinct`**:\n   - It calculates the number of subarrays with exactly `k` distinct integers by subtracting the number of subarrays with at most `k-1` distinct integers from the number of subarrays with at most `k` distinct integers.\n\nThis approach ensures that we efficiently count the required subarrays with a time complexity of O(n), where `n` is the length of the input array `nums`.", "estimated_date": 1549756800000}